`docs/` is the specification and status layer for the steno dictionary compiler in `crates/steno/` — the normative reference for the `.steno` source format and the compiler pipeline that turns it into JSON/C++ artifacts, plus an open-issues backlog.

The two content docs are tightly coupled and describe the same system from opposite ends: `steno-format.md` defines the *input* grammar (entries, directives, template operators like `%t`, `%d`, `%(EXPR)`, `%[…%]`), while `pipeline.md` defines how that input is *processed* (Pass A/B, the dual dict.steno/dict.infinite.steno paths, snippet emission). A format change — new directive, new `%x` operator, altered count-key encoding — requires updates to both: the grammar in `steno-format.md` and the corresponding pass behavior in `pipeline.md` (e.g. how `%t` slots get filled by Pass B, or how `walk` must render it identically in the infinite path). `steno-format.md` explicitly defers to the parser/stroke source code as ground truth; `pipeline.md` is the authoritative description of runtime behavior, enforced partly by differential test rather than by assertion.

`STATUS.md` tracks backlog items that reference concepts from both: e.g. "Array<> type-skipping in %t contexts" ties directly to the `%t` operator defined in `steno-format.md` and the type-append pass in `pipeline.md`; the proposed `%T` unification item foreshadows/overlaps the `%T` fused-slot marker already documented in `pipeline.md`'s infinite path — a likely near-term source of edits spanning both docs.

No intent.md exists to check divergence against.